                        <p> <hi rend="italic">Case at the Hospitals of <name type="place">Alexandria, Va.</name></hi></p><p><hi rend="initialcap">C</hi>ASE 67.—<name type="person" key="821">Private John K. Jones</name>, <name type="organization" key="339">1st Me. Cav.</name>;
                                        age 18; was admitted <date type="admit" when="1864-03-08">March 8, 1864</date>, with what was supposed to be
                                        congestive intermittent fever, but in a few days symptoms of
                                        cerebro-spinal meningitis were manifested.  The patient died
                                        comatose on the <date type="death" when="1864-03-13">13th</date>.  He was treated with calomel, saline
                                        cathartics, quinine freely administered and enemata of
                                        colocynth.   <hi rend="italic">Post-mortem</hi> examination:
                                        Extensive inflammation of the membranes of the brain and
                                        spinal cord, extending as far as the middle of the dorsal
                                        region; large lymph-deposits on the arachnoid; the
                                        ventricles of the brain were unusually dry.</p>                        
